🧠 C. Ball in Berland — Complete Notes
📌 Problem Summary
Given k valid (boy, girl) pairs
Need to select 2 pairs such that:
No same boy ❌
No same girl ❌

👉 Count number of valid ways

🧠 Core Intuition

Instead of:

“Try all pairs and check”

Think:

“Fix one pair → how many pairs can I combine with it?”

⚡ Key Observation

For a pair (a[i], b[i]), invalid pairs are:

Same boy → cntB[a[i]] - 1
Same girl → cntG[b[i]] - 1
🔥 Final Formula

For each pair:

valid=k−cntB[a[i]]−cntG[b[i]]+1

👉 Sum for all pairs and divide by 2

🧠 Why +1 ?

Because current pair is counted in both:

cntB
cntG

So we subtract it twice → add back once

📊 Step-by-Step Approach
1. Count frequency
cntB[x] = number of times boy x appears
cntG[y] = number of times girl y appears
2. For each pair
ans += (k - cntB[a[i]] - cntG[b[i]] + 1);
3. Final answer
ans /= 2;
💻 Final Code (Optimal)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#define ll long long

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int t;
    cin >> t;

    while (t--) {
        int a, b, k;
        cin >> a >> b >> k;

        vector<int> A(k), B(k);
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) cin >> A[i];
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) cin >> B[i];

        vector<int> cntA(a + 1, 0), cntB(b + 1, 0);

        // count frequencies
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            cntA[A[i]]++;
            cntB[B[i]]++;
        }

        long long ans = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            ans += (k - cntA[A[i]] - cntB[B[i]] + 1);
        }

        cout << ans / 2 << '\n';
    }

    return 0;
}
⏱️ Time Complexity
Frequency count → O(k)
Loop → O(k)

✅ Total: O(k) per test case

❌ Common Mistakes (VERY IMPORTANT)
1. Overcomplicating with maps + nested loops ❌
for(k)
   for(groups)

👉 Leads to TLE

2. Forgetting division by 2 ❌

👉 Each pair counted twice

3. Wrong counting logic ❌
Double subtract without +1
Missing self-count adjustment
4. Trying brute force ❌

👉 O(k²) → impossible

